=== 12.4 Backprop Through a Linear Layer

The most common operation in a transformer is a *linear layer*: stem:[y = Wx].

Given the upstream gradient stem:[\delta = \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial y}] (arriving from the layer above), the chain rule gives:

[stem]
++++
\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial W} = \delta \cdot x^\top
\qquad
\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial x} = W^\top \cdot \delta
++++

The first equation tells us how to update stem:[W].
The second passes the gradient backward to whatever fed stem:[x] into this layer.

==== Step 2: Linear layer backward pass

[source,scheme]
----
; Backward pass through y = W x.
; delta: upstream gradient, shape [out-dim]
; W: weight matrix used in the forward pass, shape [out-dim x in-dim]
; x: input used in the forward pass, shape [in-dim]
; Returns: grad-W (same shape as W) and grad-x (same shape as x).
(define (linear-backward delta W x)
  (let* ((out-dim (matrix-rows W))
         (in-dim  (matrix-cols W))
         (grad-W  (make-matrix out-dim in-dim))
         (grad-x  (make-vector in-dim 0.0)))
    ; grad-W[i,j] = delta[i] * x[j]  (outer product)
    (let loop-i ((i 0))
      (when (< i out-dim)
        (let loop-j ((j 0))
          (when (< j in-dim)
            (matrix-set! grad-W i j
              (* (vector-ref delta i) (vector-ref x j)))
            (loop-j (+ j 1))))
        (loop-i (+ i 1))))
    ; grad-x[j] = sum_i W[i,j] * delta[i]  (W^T delta)
    (let loop-j ((j 0))
      (when (< j in-dim)
        (let loop-i ((i 0))
          (when (< i out-dim)
            (vector-set! grad-x j
              (+ (vector-ref grad-x j)
                 (* (matrix-ref W i j) (vector-ref delta i))))
            (loop-i (+ i 1))))
        (loop-j (+ j 1))))
    (cons grad-W grad-x)))
----

=== 12.6 Accumulating Gradients Across the Sequence

We compute the softmax-CE gradient independently at each position stem:[t].
But all positions share the same unembedding matrix stem:[W_u] (and the same transformer weights).
Their gradient contributions must be _summed_ before updating any weight.

==== Step 4: Summing gradient contributions

[source,scheme]
----
; Add together per-position gradient matrices for a shared weight.
(define (accumulate-gradients grad-list)
  (let* ((m (matrix-rows (car grad-list)))
         (n (matrix-cols (car grad-list)))
         (total (make-matrix m n)))
    (for-each (lambda (g)
                (let loop-i ((i 0))
                  (when (< i m)
                    (let loop-j ((j 0))
                      (when (< j n)
                        (matrix-set! total i j
                          (+ (matrix-ref total i j) (matrix-ref g i j)))
                        (loop-j (+ j 1))))
                    (loop-i (+ i 1)))))
              grad-list)
    total))
----

The more a weight influenced the output at many positions, the larger (and more reliable) its accumulated gradient.
